The book generalizes Fourier analysis on locally compact Abelian groups by introducing the concept of Pontriagin duality, where the characters of the group form a dual group, denoted as ![
$$\\hat{G}$$
](A79351_2_En_2_Chapter_IEq10.gif). This dual group has a topology defined by uniform convergence on compact sets. The Fourier expansion is replaced by the Fourier inversion formula:

![
$$\\displaystyle{f\(g\) =\\int _{\\hat{G}}\\hat{f}\(\\chi \)\\,\\chi \(g\)\\,\\mathrm{d}\\chi,\\quad\\hat{f}\(\\chi \) =\\int _{G}f\(g\)\\,\\overline{\\chi \(g\)}\\,\\mathrm{d}g.}$$
](A79351_2_En_2_Chapter_Equa.gif)

This formulation exhibits symmetry between the original group G and its dual group ![
$$\\hat{G}$$
](A79351_2_En_2_Chapter_IEq11.gif). Similarly, the Plancherel formula transitions from a sum over characters to an integral over the dual group, incorporating the continuous nature of characters in this setting.
